# Hebrew / RTL chat (always)

## Always

On every assistant reply in Cursor chat, wrap all non-code narrative (explanations, headings, lists, prose) in:

```html
<div dir="rtl">

… markdown here …

</div>
```

Do not place fenced code blocks inside that div; keep them after the closing `</div>` or in their own `dir="ltr"` wrapper.

If HTML is stripped, start each Hebrew-heavy paragraph with RLM (U+200F, `‏`).

## Code and technical content

Keep code, commands, paths, logs, and stack traces LTR. Use a plain fenced block or:

```html
<div dir="ltr">

```text
…
```

</div>
```

## Mixed Hebrew and English

For English tokens inside Hebrew (file names, APIs, identifiers), use LRM (U+200E, `‎`) and RLM (U+200F) around the Latin segment when visual order is wrong.

## Exception

Only skip the RTL wrapper if the user explicitly asks for an all-LTR layout for that message.

## Limitation

Chat panel CSS is controlled by Cursor; this rule improves direction and bidi in markdown/HTML where supported. IDE-wide RTL may still need an extension.
